Reflection:
Today, you learned that beauty often comes from guilt (Medici) and spite (Brunelleschi). Tomorrow, we look at the man who burned his own paintings.


üèõÔ∏è DAY 2: FULL LESSON CONTENT
Title: Day 2: The Bonfire of the Vanities
Progress Bar: [======..............] (Day 2/7)
üìú Part 1: The Context (The Party is Over)
Reading Time: 5 Minutes
The History:
Yesterday, under the Medici, Florence was a 24/7 party of philosophy and art. But parties end.
By the late 1490s, the bank was losing money, and the people were hungry. When people are hungry, they get radical.
The Power Shift:
Enter Girolamo Savonarola. He wasn't a banker; he was a fanatical monk.
He looked at the art, the makeup, and the poetry, and he didn't see beauty. He saw corruption. He preached that the Medici were leading Florence to Hell.
His sermons were terrifying. When the French army invaded (by coincidence), the people believed Savonarola was a prophet. They kicked the Medici out. Florence went from a carnival to a monastery overnight.
üó£Ô∏è Part 2: The Drama (Burning the Art)
Reading Time: 5 Minutes
The Scandal:
Savonarola organized the "Bonfire of the Vanities" (1497).
He sent boys door-to-door to collect "vanities."
What is a vanity? Mirrors, cosmetics, fancy clothes, musical instruments, and art.
They built a pyramid in the city square, 60 feet high, and set it on fire.
The Tragedy:
Sandro Botticelli, the sensitive artist who painted the famous Birth of Venus, fell under Savonarola‚Äôs spell.
Botticelli was terrified for his soul. According to biography, Botticelli himself threw some of his own paintings onto the fire. The "Golden Age" was burned to ash by the very people who created it.
üé® Part 3: The Masterpiece (The Survivor)
Reading Time: 10 Minutes
The Work: The Birth of Venus
The Artist: Sandro Botticelli
Visual Decoding:
This painting survived the fire.
Look at Venus (the center). She is floating on a shell. She is nude.
This was shocking. For 1,000 years, the only female nude allowed in art was Eve (shameful). Botticelli made nudity divine again.
She isn't standing correctly (she has no weight); she looks like she is cut out of paper. This wasn't a mistake‚Äîit was a style choice to show she belonged to a spiritual world, not the physical one.
Your "Cocktail Party" Fact:
Savonarola eventually went too far. He annoyed the Pope. The Pope excommunicated him. The people of Florence turned on the monk, and a year after the Bonfire, they burned Savonarola in the exact same spot he burned the art.
‚öîÔ∏è The Day 2 Challenge (Active Recall)
The Villain: Who convinced Florence to burn their art?

Lorenzo de Medici

Girolamo Savonarola (Correct)

The Pope
The Shift: Why was The Birth of Venus controversial?

It was the first non-Biblical female nude since antiquity. (Correct)

It was painted in oil.

It depicted the Virgin Mary.
The Fate: What happened to the monk Savonarola?

He became Pope.

He was burned at the stake. (Correct)

He fled to France.

üèõÔ∏è DAY 3: FULL LESSON CONTENT
Title: Day 3: The Failed Experiment
Progress Bar: [=========...........] (Day 3/7)
üìú Part 1: The Context (The Resume)
Reading Time: 5 Minutes
The History:
Leonardo da Vinci is 30 years old. He is talented, but he has a reputation: He never finishes anything. He leaves Florence for Milan to find a new patron, Duke Ludovico Sforza.
The Power Shift:
Leonardo writes the famous "Sforza Resume." He lists 10 skills to get the job.
Number 1-9 are about war: "I can build bridges," "I can divert rivers," "I can make armored tanks."
Only at number 10 does he add: "Also, I can paint."
The Duke hired him. Not as a painter, but as a military engineer and party planner.
üó£Ô∏è Part 2: The Drama (The Peeling Wall)
Reading Time: 5 Minutes
The Scandal:
The Duke asked Leonardo to paint the dining hall of a monastery.
Normal "Fresco" painting (painting on wet plaster) requires speed. You have to finish before the plaster dries.
Leonardo hated speed. He wanted to think, stare, and layer.
The Failure:
So, Leonardo invented a new mix of oil and tempera to paint on dry wall. It allowed him to take his time.
It was a disaster. The paint didn't bond. Within 20 years, the greatest painting in the world began to flake off the wall. Today, only about 20% of the original paint remains. It is a masterpiece that is slowly dying.
üé® Part 3: The Masterpiece (The Betrayal)
Reading Time: 10 Minutes
The Work: The Last Supper
The Artist: Leonardo da Vinci
Visual Decoding:
This isn't a dinner party; it is an explosion.
Leonardo captured the specific second after Jesus said: "One of you will betray me."
Look at the reaction of the disciples. They are grouped in threes. They are terrified.
Jesus forms a calm triangle in the chaos.
Your "Cocktail Party" Fact:
The prior of the monastery complained that Leonardo was working too slowly. Leonardo told the Duke: "I am searching for a face evil enough to model for Judas. If I can‚Äôt find one, I will use the face of the prior." The prior stopped complaining.
‚öîÔ∏è The Day 3 Challenge (Active Recall)
