üèõÔ∏è DAY 4: FULL LESSON CONTENT
Title: Day 4: The Giant in the Stone
Progress Bar: [============........] (Day 4/7)
üìú Part 1: The Context (The Trash Marble)
Reading Time: 5 Minutes
The History:
The Medici were kicked out. Florence was a Republic again. But they were surrounded by enemies (The Pope, The French, The Medici trying to return).
The city government wanted a statue to represent their strength. They needed a symbol of a "small guy defeating a giant." They needed David.
The Problem:
They had no money for marble.
There was a massive block in the cathedral yard called "The Giant." Two other sculptors had tried to carve it years ago and failed, gouging a hole in the middle. It had been sitting in the rain for 40 years. It was considered garbage.
üó£Ô∏è Part 2: The Drama (The Rivalry)
Reading Time: 5 Minutes
The Scandal:
Leonardo da Vinci was consulted, but said the stone was unusable.
A 26-year-old Michelangelo stepped up. He said, "I can do it."
He built a shed around the block so no one could see him work. He barely ate. He slept in his boots. He worked with a fury called terribilit√†.
When he revealed it, the city was stunned. Leonardo suggested hiding it in a dark corner (out of jealousy). The city ignored him and put it right in front of the government palace.
üé® Part 3: The Masterpiece (The Watcher)
Reading Time: 10 Minutes
The Work: The David
The Artist: Michelangelo
Visual Decoding:
Most Davids show him after killing Goliath (holding the head).
Michelangelo shows him before.
Look at his eyes. He is glaring into the distance. He is terrified but focused.
Look at his right hand. It is too big. This is intentional‚ÄîDavid was known as "manu fortis" (strong of hand).
Your "Cocktail Party" Fact:
The pupils of David‚Äôs eyes are carved in the shape of hearts (actually indented drills) to catch the light so they look intense from the ground. Also, because the block was previously ruined, the statue is extremely thin from side-to-side.
‚öîÔ∏è The Day 4 Challenge (Active Recall)
